				<!-- #BeginEditable "page-title" -->
				<h1>Capital Gain and Loss Categories</h1>
				<!-- #EndEditable -->

				<!-- #BeginEditable "page-subhead" -->
				<!-- #EndEditable -->
		
				<div id="byline">
				
					<!-- #BeginEditable "byline" -->
					<p>By <a href="../fairmark/about.htm">Kaye A. Thomas</a> </p>
					<!-- #EndEditable -->
				</div> <!-- byline -->
					
					<div id="summary">
						<!-- #BeginEditable "summary" -->
						<p>Capital gains and losses are divided between short-term and 
				long-term, and there are other special categories.</p>
						<!-- #EndEditable -->
					</div> <!-- summary -->

			    <!-- #BeginEditable "story-p1" -->
			    
    <p>The theory behind these rules is that you gather all the gains and losses within a
    single category to figure out the overall result for that category before combining the
    results with another category. For example, if you have both gains and losses in the
    short-term category, you'll combine them to find the net amount of short-term gain or
    loss. You can't mix categories until after you've worked out the net amount within each
    category. After that, if you have gain in one category and loss in another, you combine
    the two.</p>
			    
			    <!-- #EndEditable -->
			    
			    <p class="noprint">(continued below)</p>
			    
			    <div id="google-inset-300">

<script type="text/javascript"><!--
google_ad_client = "pub-0101170206512133";
/* Open Air text 300x250 created 4/7/11 */
google_ad_slot = "5755883784";
google_ad_width = 300;
google_ad_height = 250;
//-->
</script>
<script type="text/javascript"
src="http://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/show_ads.js">
</script>

						

				</div>

			    
			    
			    
				<!-- #BeginEditable "content" -->
    <h3>Holding period</h3>
    <p>For the most part, the categories of gain or loss are determined by your <em>holding
    period</em> for the asset you sold. (There are also some special categories for certain
    types of assets.) For stocks, your holding period is generally determined by the amount of
    time that elapses between the trade date of your purchase and the trade date of your sale.
    But if you acquired your stock other than by purchase your holding period may relate to
    some earlier date. For example, if you receive additional stock as a result of a stock
    split, the new stock has the same holding period as the stock you already held.</p>
    <h3>Short-term gain</h3>
    <p>If the trade date of the sale is one year or less after the trade date of the purchase,
    you have a <em>short-term capital gain</em>. For example, if you bought on May 12,
    2003 and sold on May 12, 2004 you have a short-term gain, because you must hold for <em>more
    than</em> one year to have a long-term gain. Short-term capital gain is taxed at the same
    rate as ordinary income (like wages and interest income), unless you have a capital loss
    that eliminates it.</p>
				<p>If your gain isn't short-term, then it's long-term.</p>
    <h3>Long-term gain</h3>
    <p>If the trade date of the sale is more than one year after the trade date 
	of the purchase you have a long-term capital gain. As of 2008 you pay 0% tax on this 
	category of gain if it falls into the 10% or 15% tax bracket; otherwise you 
	pay 15%.</p>
    			<p class="indent"><strong>Example:</strong>
      Before counting any capital gain, your taxable income is in the 15%
      bracket, $4,000 below where the 25% bracket begins. You have a $10,000
      long-term capital gain. The first $4,000 of this capital gain falls into
      the 15% bracket and is taxed at 0%. The rest is taxed at 15%.</p>
    <h3>Investment and other?</h3>
				<p>Some people are concerned that they cannot use capital losses 
				from one source to offset capital gain from another source. 
				Generally this is not a problem. For example, if you have a 
				capital gain from selling your home (beyond the amount you can 
				exclude), you can use a capital loss from a stock investment to 
				reduce or eliminate that gain.</p>
				<h3>Additional categories</h3>
    <p>There are additional categories of long-term gain or loss, summarized below. Each of
    the rates mentioned below is a <em>maximum</em> rate. That means the rate will reduce your
    taxes if you would otherwise pay a higher rate &#151; but it won't increase your taxes if
    your regular tax rate is lower. For example, if you receive 28% gain when your regular
    rate is 15%, your tax on that gain will be 15% unless the gain is large enough to push you
    up into the next tax bracket.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Certain gains from <em>collectibles</em> are treated as 28% gain 
			even if it would otherwise qualify for the 15% (or 0%) rate.</li>
          <li>Certain gains from sales of real property are
        taxed at a special 25% rate.</li>
          <li>The law also includes special rates for property
        held more than five years, but these rates are now superseded by the 5% 
			and 15% rates.</li>
        </ul>
    <p>This may seem a little complicated &mdash; and it is. Perhaps Congress will 
	simplify capital gains at some point. Meanwhile these are the capital gain 
	categories we have to deal with.</p>
			    
			    <!-- #EndEditable -->
			    
			    
			    
